[ProMED-mail thanks Dr. Hirsch for providing additional details about the cases of hemorrhagic fever in Divinópolis, Minas Gerais state. Although a confirmed diagnosis is mentioned, the etiological agent involved in these cases is not reported. ProMED would appreciate additional information about the etiology when it is available. Is it Brazilian spotted fever?

A 2016 published report states, "In Brazil _Amblyomma sculptum_ from _Amblyomma cajennense_ complex is a tick species with a rather broad distribution encompassing the Cerrado Biome and devastated areas of the Atlantic rainforest. This species is also the major vector to humans of _Rickettsia rickettsii_, agent of the Brazilian spotted fever. Main primary hosts for the adult stage and frequently associated to high environmental infestation levels are the native capybaras and tapirs and a domestic host, the horse. Recent, however, solely circumstantial evidence, has shown that pigs (_Sus scrofa_) domestic, feral or exotic (wild boars) as well as wild suidae may maintain _A. sculptum_ populations as well." https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2405939016301678.

A map of Divinópolis showing the location of the park can be accessed with the URL in Dr. Hirsch's comments above, and a HealthMap/ProMED map available at: Divinópolis, Minas Gerais, Brazil: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5965116,16253. - Mod.TY]
